         <div type="entry">
                <head>Çiçek, Julius Yeshu</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Cicek-Julius-Yeshu</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/144</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">135</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="100"/>
                    <idno type="althead" subtype="altorder">Julius Yeshu Çiçek</idno>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/422</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Monastic founder and publisher.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(1941–2005) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>He was born in Upper Kafro and studied Syriac in <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/al-Zafaran-Dayr">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/69">Dayr
                        al-Zaʿfarān</placeName>
                        </ref> under <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Dolabani-Philoxenos-Yuhanon">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/454">Dolabani</persName>
                        </ref> who ordained him
                        a deacon in 1958. In 1961 he became a monk and became the principal of the
                        seminary at <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Gabriel-Monastery-of-Mor">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/226">Monastery of Mor Gabriel</placeName>
                        </ref> in 1962. In 1977 he became a Patriarchal
                        Vicar to Central Europe and the Benelux, and he was consecrated a <abbr>bp.</abbr> in
                        1979. He established St. Ephrem Monastery in the Netherlands at
                        Glane-Losser, and he was instrumental in the establishment of two other
                        monasteries in Europe, <choice>
                            <sic>i.e. </sic>
                            <corr>i.e., </corr>
                        </choice>Mar Awgen in Switzerland and Mar Yaʿqub in
                        Germany (Warburg). He established Bar Hebraeus Verlag where he edited and
                        published many books scribed in his own hand prior to the development of
                        computer fonts, then moved to using computer fonts. He established and
                        edited <hi rend="italic">Kolo Süryoyo</hi> from 1978 until his death in
                        2005. Most of the anonymous editorials, articles, and news reports written
                        in Syriac in <hi rend="italic">Kolo Süryoyo</hi> are by him, but he rarely
                        published works under his own name.</p>
                    <p>See <ref target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/fig/36">Fig. 36</ref>.</p>
                </div>
